IRD-009 and its  antimicrobial and cytotoxic activities

Anelize Bauermeistera  , Francisco das C. L. Pintob, Talita C.  T. Medeirosa, Larissa C. Almeidac, Leonardo J. Silvad, Itamar S. de Meloe, Tiago  D. Zucchif, Letícia V. Costa-Lotufoc  adepartamento de Química, Faculdade de Filosofia, ciências e letras de ribeirão Preto, universidade de são  Paulo,  ribeirão  Preto,  Brazil;  bdepartamento  de  Química  orgânica  e  Inorgânica,  universidade  Federal  do  ceará, Fortaleza, Brazil;  cdepartamento de Farmacologia, Instituto de ciências Biomédicas, universidade de  são Paulo, são Paulo, Brazil; dcollege of agriculture “luiz de Queiroz”, universidade de são Paulo, Piracicaba,  Brazil;  elaboratory  of  environmental  Microbiology,  National  Brazilian  research  corporation  -  eMBraPa  eNVIroNMeNt, Jaguariuna, Brazil; fdepartamento de Pesquisa & desenvolvimento, aGrIValle, salto, Brazil CONTACT  luiz a. ABSTRACT A  new  polycyclic  antibiotic,  pradimicin-IRD,  was  isolated  from  actinobacteria  Amycolatopsis  sp.  IRD-009  recovered  from  soil  of  Brazilian  rainforest  undergoing  restoration  area.  This  molecule  is  the  major  compound  produced  in  solid  culture  media.  The  new  compound  was  detected  by  a  focused  method  of  precursor  ion  (high-performance liquid chromatography coupled to tandem mass  spectrometer) developed previously to identify unusual aminoglycosyl  sugar  moieties. The  compound  was  isolated  and  its  structure  was,  therefore,  elucidated  by  high-resolution  mass  spectrometry,  and  1D  and  2D  nuclear  magnetic  resonance  experiments.  Pradimicin- IRD displayed potential antimicrobial activity against Streptococcus  agalactiae  (MIC  3.1  μg/mL),  Pseudomonas  aeruginosa  (MIC  3.1  μg/ mL) and Staphylococcus aureus (MIC 3.1 μg/mL), and also cytotoxicity  against tumour and non-tumour cell lines with IC50 values ranging  from 0.8 μM in HCT-116 colon carcinoma cells to 2.7 μM in MM 200  melanoma cells. Particularly, these biological properties are described  for the first time for this chemical class.   luizmoraes@ffclrp.usp.br ARTICLE HISTORY received 6 december 2017  accepted 25 January 2018 KEYWORDS actinobacteria; antibacterial  activity; cytotoxic activity;  natural products

Pradimicins  and  benanomicins  are  antifungal  compounds  with  related  structures  which  were described almost at the same time. They are characterised by an aglycone of benzo[α] naphthacenequinone, which usually presents a substitution by a D-amino acid and hexose  sugar, usually produced by species of the genus Actinomadura (Gomi et al. 1988; Tsunakawa  et al. 1989; Aburaki, Okuyama, et al. ; Aburaki, Yamashita, et al. 1993). Regarding the biological  properties,  pradimicins  are  reported  with  in  vivo  antifungal  activity,  along  with  antiviral  properties, against HIV-14 and hepatitis C viruses (Tanabe et al. 1988; Bertaux et al. 2007).  More specifically, as mechanism of action, these molecules have the property of binding to  terminal D-manosides of the cell wall, forming a ternary complex with calcium, which favours  the lysis of fungal cell membranes (Walsh and Giri 1997); that is the reason why they are  present as such strong antifungal activity. In this work, we described the isolation and struc- tural characterisation of a new pradimicin IRD, with potential antimicrobial activity against  many bacteria that cause bovine mastitis. Moreover, this new structure showed cytotoxic  activity  against  tumour  cell  lines,  a  biological  property  observed  for  the  first  time  for  a  pradimicin derivative. 2.  Results and discussion 2.1.  Taxonomy of the actinobacteria IRD-009

The actinobacteria IRD-009 was identified as Amycolatopsis sp. IRD-009 based on the 16S  rRNA gene similarity. This classification was also supported by the phylogenetic analysis in  which the isolate was retrieved within the mesophilic members of Amycolatopsis (Figure S1)  (Zucchi et al. 2012). Indeed, the isolate formed a new phyletic line at the periphery of the  Amycolatopsis albidoflavus 16S rRNA gene subclade; a result supported by all tree-making  algorithms and by a bootstrap value of 80%. The organism shares a 16S rRNA gene similarity  of 99.1% with the strain type of A. albidoflavus; a value which corresponds to 12 different  nucleotides at 1357 sites. The corresponding values of the 16S rRNA gene similarity to other  members of the A. albidoflavus clade are below 99.0%. 2.2.  Structure characterisation Pradimicin-IRD  (PRM-IRD)  (1)  (Figure  1)  was  isolated  as  a  dark  red  powder.  Its  molecular  formula, C37H41NO12, was deduced by HRESIMS spectrum from the protonated molecule  [M + H]+ (exact mass m/z 692.2702; exp. mass m/z 692.2704, error 2 ppm). The degree of  unsaturation calculated by the molecular formula was eighteen. [𝛼]25  (c 0.01, CH3OH).  The  UV  spectrum  (Figure  S2)  (MeOH–H2O)  displayed  λmax  219,  285  and  460 nm. The  CID  (collision induced dissociation) spectrum (Figure S3) suggested that PRM-IRD consisted of  an  aromatic  aglycone  and  one  O-aminoglycoside.  The  structure  of  the  newly  isolated  pradimicin-IRD was determined on the basis of 1H, 13C and 2D NMR experiments (Figures  S4–S10).

All NMR data for PRM-IRD are summarised in Table S1. The 1H NMR spectrum (Figure S4)  displayed  signals  for  two  chelated  hydroxyl  groups  at  δ  15.70  (s  br),  13.27  (s)  and  three  aromatic protons at δ 7.31 (s, H-7), 7.26 (s, H-12) and 6.51 (s, H-4) corresponding to the agly- cone moiety. The H-5 (δ 4.49) and H-6 (δ 4.26) are coupling forming a doublet with J = 3.8 Hz,  Figure 1. structures of pradimicin a (Prd-a) and pradimicin Ird (PrM-Ird). corresponding to axial-axial positions. Furthermore, the 1H NMR spectrum displayed three  signals for methoxy groups at δ 3.99 (s, 11-OCH3), 3.78 (s, 15-OCH3) and 3.30 (s, 6-OCH3) from  the aglycone moiety, and also two methyl bound to a nitrogen at δ 2.37 (s br, 4′-N(CH3)2),  belonging to the aminoglycosyl moiety. It was also observed the signal of the hydrogen  (H-2′) from the anomeric carbon at δ 5.25 (d, J = 3.0 Hz).

The 13C NMR spectrum (Figure S5) for compound 1 indicated the presence of 37 carbon  atoms consisting of 3 methoxy, 4 methyl and 2 additional methyl corresponding to N(CH3)2  at δ 35.8, 1 methylene group, 8 methine groups (3 in the aromatic region, and 5 oxygenated  carbons, including 1 anomeric), 19 non-protonated carbons (2 ketone carbonyl at δ 188.1  and 180.0, 1 carbonyl carbon at δ 169.8, 15 aromatic carbons, of which, 4 are oxygenated at  δ 167.8, 163.1, 160.2 and 158.1, and 1 aliphatic). These data highlighted the presence of an  aminoglycoside moiety, and they are also consistent with the benzo[α]naphthacenequinone  system from pradimicins (Felsenstein 1981; Van der Meer et al. 2007) with some minor and  interesting differences.

The methoxy positions were determined by HMBC correlations (Figure S8 and S9) from  6-OCH3 (δ 3.30) to C-6 (δ 79.5); 11-OCH3 (δ 3.99) to C-11 (δ 163.1); and 15-OCH3 (δ 3.78) to  C-15 (δ 169.8). The methyl positions were also determined by HMBC correlations from 3-CH3  (δ 2.14) to C-2 (δ 126.1), C-3 (δ 133.5) and C-4 (δ 119.5); 10-CH3 (δ 2.10) to C-9 (δ 160.2), C-10  (δ 115.8) and C-11 (δ 163.1). The aminoglycosyl moiety at C-5 was determined by NOESY  correlations (Figure S10) from H-5 (δ 4.49) to H-2′ (δ 5.25). The NOESY correlation from H-5  to 6-OCH3 (δ 3.30) corroborates to the relative configurations of C-5 and C-6, which is con- sistent with the reported configuration of pradimicins (Tsunakawa et al. 1989; Saitoh et al.  1993).

Related to the aglycone moiety, instead of an amino acid at C-15, the PRM-IRD has an  ester functional group. This fact suggested that the amino acid ligase that ligates a D-alanine  unit in pradimicins produced by Actinomadura hibisca P157-2 (Kim et al. 2007), is not present  or is muted in Amycolatopsis sp. IRD-009. The methoxyl at this position was confirmed by its  correlation with C-15 in HMBC and also with the methyl at C-3 in NOESY spectra. Sawada et  al. (1990) described two pradimicins with hydroxyl group instead of the amino acid, dealanyl  pradimicinone and pradimicin M. However, the first one was obtained by acid hydrolysis of  pradimicins A and C; and the second pradimicin was produced by a mutant of A. hibisca,  which  in  this  case,  the  stereochemistry  of  C-5  and  C-6  is  different  from  the  others  in  literature. NATURAL PRODUCT RESEARCH   The methyl group at C-10 is also unusual for pradimicin chemical class. It was confirmed  by HSQC and also due its correlations observed in HMBC with C-9, C-10 and C-11. The meth- ylation at this position might be attributed to the presence of S-adenosylmethionine (SAM),  which  generates  a  rare  system  of  polyketides  backbone. The  presence  of  SAM  could  be  evidenced by the high level of methylation in PRM-IRD compared to those in literature, and  furthermore, it will be evaluated in a future work. This fact makes this actinobacteria very  interesting to be applied for biotransformation products of biotechnological interest.

Considering the glycoside moiety, that is the first report in which natural products from  pradimicin class contain a N,N-dimethyl-L-vancosamine at C-5 with (2′R, 4′S, 5′S, 6′S) config- uration. It was confirmed by the interaction between the protons at 4′-CH3 and 6′ observed  in NOESY spectrum (Figure S10). Commonly, pradimicins have two sugar moieties, being  one of them an aminoglycoside. Interestingly, PRM-IRD contains only an aminosugar. 2.3.  Biological activity Pradimicins are very well described as antifungal and antiviral agent. However, we decided  to evaluate its effect against bacteria that causes bovine mastitis in dairy cows. Despite some  antibiotics, such as tetracycline, cephalexin and penicillin, have already been applied against  bovine mastitis, any one of them are completely efficient in the treatment. The ongoing  appearance of antimicrobial resistance makes necessary the continuous research on new  antibiotics and/or more efficient therapies. Most of the time, the only possibility available  for bovine mastitis in dairy cows consists on the elimination of the herd, which causes sig- nificant economic losses to dairy farmers (Boonyayatra et al. 2016).

First of all, the crude extract was used to investigate the antibacterial potential against  eleven bacteria that causes bovine mastitis, and two different Escherichia coli strains by disc  diffusion assay (Table S2). The strongest activities were observed for Streptococcus agalactiae  – 97; Staphylococcus aureus – 211; E. coli ATCC 25.922; and Pseudomonas aeruginosa ATCC  27.859. Therefore, these bacteria were selected to test the isolated PRM-IRD by MIC assay  (Table S3). PRM-IRD showed the strongest activity against S. agalactiae (MIC 3.125 μg/mL),  P. aeruginosa (MIC 3.125 μg/mL) and S. aureus (MIC 3.125 μg/mL). Interestingly, PRM-IRD was  thus more potent than the positive control tetracycline (MIC 6.25 μg/mL) against S. aureus. Still considering the great structure difference in PRM-IRD, we decided to test its antitu- mour potential. Results of tumour growth inhibition obtained from MTT 72-h assay presented  the sensibility of colorectal carcinoma, melanoma and breast cancer cell lines for PRM-IRD  as well as normal retinal cell line. The half maximum inhibitory concentration (IC50) of the  evaluated molecule for each cell line is comparable to the positive control (Doxorubicin),  indicating its considerable cytotoxicity activity (Table S3). The cytotoxic mechanism of action  of PRM-IRD is underway in our laboratory.

In regards to the biological activity of Pradimicins, previous studies corroborate to the  antifungal and antiviral properties of this compound. The antifungal mechanism of action  of pradimicins is characterised by fungal cell membrane lysis, which is resulted from a ternary  complex  consisting  of  D-mannoside,  pradimicin  and  calcium  (Walsh  and  Giri  1997).  Pradimicins also inhibit the syncytium formation promoted by viruses (Van der Meer et al.  2007; Balzarini et al. 2010). Nevertheless, the inhibitory potential against bacteria that causes  bovine  mastitis,  as  well  as,  the  cytotoxicity  in  tumour  cell  lines  had not  been  previ- ously described for pradimicins. 3.1.  General experimental procedures 1H and 13C NMR spectra were acquired using Bruker AVANCE-500 spectrometer. Chemical  shift values were referenced to residual solvent signals for dimethyl sulphoxide-d6 (δH/δC,  2.50/39.51), 2D NMR experiments were performed using standard pulse sequences. HRESIMS experiment was performed in an UltrOTOF-Q (Bruker Daltonics) mass spectrom- eter equipped with a quadrupole time-of-ﬂight mass analyzer, with an electrospray ionisation  source. The conditions used were as follows: 3.2 kV capillary and 500 V cone voltage, 180 °C  gas temperature, 0.4 Bar gas pressure, 4 L/min drying gas, flow at 5 μL/mL. accordingly to Bauermeister et al. (2016). 3.2.  Bacterial isolation and taxonomy Actinobacteria were kindly provided from Coleção de Microrganismos de Importância Agrícola  e Ambiental (CCMA, EMBRAPA, Brazil). Strain IRD-009 was recovered from SM3 agar plate,(Tan  et al. 2006) which was inoculated with a suspension of a soil sample from Brazilian rainforest  undergoing restoration at Iracemápolis/São Paulo, and incubated at 28 °C for 21 days.

The phylogenetic position of strain IRD-009 was assigned by 16S rRNA gene sequence  analysis. Genomic DNA extraction, PCR amplification and 16S rRNA gene sequencing were  achieved according to Zucchi et al. (2011). The almost complete 16S rRNA gene sequence  (1368 nucleotides [nt]) was aligned using MEGA software version 7.0 (Nei and Kumar 2000;  Kumar  et  al.  2016)  against  corresponding  sequences  of  closely  related  type  strains  of  Amycolatopsis, using EzTaxon-e server database (Kim et al. 2012). Phylogenetic trees were  inferred by tree-making algorithms from MEGA package: maximum-likelihood (Felsenstein  1981), maximum-parsimony (Fitch 1971) and neighbour-joining (Saitou and Nei 1987). The  appropriate nucleotide substitutions for the maximum-likelihood analysis were selected by  the  Bayesian  Information  Criterion  (BIC)  using  the  MEGA  7  software  and  it  followed  the  Tamura-Nei method (TN93+G+I) (Tamura and Nei 1993). The topologies of the evolutionary  trees were evaluated by a bootstrap analysis (Felsenstein 1985) of the neighbour-joining  method based on a 1000 replicates. The phylogenetic root was inferred using Actinokineospora  riparia (GenBank accession number AF114802) as out-group. The GenBank accession number  for the 16S rRNA gene sequence of Amycolatopsis sp. IRD-009 is KY767918. 3.3.  Production and isolation

Amycolatopsis sp. IRD-009 was grown at GYEA (glucose-yeast extract agar) medium (a total  of 300 mL) plates (Gordon and Mihm 1962) at room temperature (± 28 °C) during 15 days.  All media were macerated and submerged with methanol:butanol (8:2) in Erlenmeyer flasks,  immediately sealed afterwards. The flasks were maintained under shaking (150 rpm) over- night. The mixture was filtered and the solvent was dried under low pressure at a rotary  evaporator. 180 mg of crude extract (0.6 mg/mL) was obtained. The extraction yield was evaluated with different solvents, such as ethyl acetate, dichlo- romethane, methanol, butanol and mixtures of them. The samples obtained were analysed  Crude extracts (300 μg/mL in acetonitrile) were submitted to a precursor ion method  NATURAL PRODUCT RESEARCH   by HPLC-MS/MS, and the ion m/z 692 was observed for all of them, which proves that the  molecule is not an artefact from the extraction procedure. The crude extract produced by the actinobacteria Amycolatopsis sp. IRD-009 (180 mg)  was pre-purified in glass column (130,0 × 1,8 cm) containing 30 g of Sephadex LH-20 with  methanol. The fraction containing PRM-IRD (35 mg) was submitted to HPLC semi-preparative,  applying a C18 column Zorbax Eclipse XDB (Agilent, 250 × 9.4 mm, 5 μm). The mobile phases  consist of water and methanol, being used a linear gradient 10–100% in 35 min, with 4.0 mL/ min flow rate and 500 μL injection volume. It was obtained 16 mg of isolated PRM-IRD (96  % of purity). 3.4.  Pradimicin-IRD (PRM-IRD) (1) Dark red powder. [𝛼]25 Positive HRESIMS m/z 692.2704 [M + H]+ (calcd C37H41NO12 data, see Table S1. 3.5.  Biological activity

The  crude  extract  IRD-009  (10 mg/mL)  was  tested  by  disc  diffusion  assay  accordingly  to  Bauer and Kirby method.(Bauer et al. 1966). PRM-IRD was used to determine the minimum  inhibitory concentrations (MIC), which were obtained by serial dilution using 96-well micr- otitre plates (100–0.158 μg/mL). Tetracycline (10 mg/mL) was used as positive control. 3.6.  Cell culture and MTT assay MM 200 (melanoma) and HCT-116 (colon adenorcarcinoma) cells were grown in Roswell  Park Memorial Institute medium (RPMI), while MCF-7 (breast carcinoma) and RPE (non-tu- mour retinal pigment epithelial cells) were grown in Dulbecco’s modified medium (DMEM)  with GlutaMAX. Both media were supplemented with 10% fetal bovine serum (FBS) and 1%  penicillin streptomycin. Cells were kept in an incubator with 5% CO2 at 37 °C. For MTT assay,  the cells were seeded on 96-well plates at a density of 1 × 104 per well with 200 μL culture  medium.  After  24 h,  PRM-IRD  (0.0032–50  μM)  was  added  to  the  cultures  and  incubated  during 72 h. DMSO (0.05%) was used a negative control and the antineoplastic compound  doxorubicin (0.00064–10 μM) was used as positive control. After treatment, culture media were replaced by fresh media containing MTT solution  (0.5 mg/mL) and incubated during 3 h. The MTT solution was, then, removed and the plates  dried at 35 °C for 30 min. The formazan product was solubilised in 150 μL DMSO and the  absorbance was obtained at 540 nm. The IC50 values and their 95% confidence interval were  calculated by sigmoidal nonlinear regression using GraphPad Prism 5 software.
